[1]
Date: Fri 19 Dec 2008
Source: AP via International Herald Tribune [edited]
<http://www.iht.com/bin/printfriendly.php?id=18816699>


Philippines appeals for help in probing pig virus
-------------------------------------------------
The Philippine government has appealed for
international help in investigating an outbreak
of the Ebola Reston virus that has for the 1st
time infected pigs but is not harmful to humans,
officials said Friday [19 Dec 2008]. Bureau of
Animal Industry Director Davinio Catbagan this
week [15-19 Dec 2008] wrote to the Rome-based
Food and Agriculture Organization [FAO]
requesting official assistance, after authorities
quarantined 3 hog farms in the northern Philippines.

The Agriculture Department said in a statement it
sent 28 pigs' tissue samples for testing to the
Plum Island Animal Disease Center in the U.S. and 6 were found positive.

Dr. Angel Mateo, director of the bureau's Animal
Welfare Division, said Friday no pigs had died of
Ebola Reston and a 2nd round of local tests
showed animals were no longer infected. "At the
moment, the test results from the quarantined
area are negative," he said, adding more tests were planned.

Authorities say the Ebola Reston virus -- 1st
discovered among crab-eating monkeys south of
Manila in 1989 -- has caused no known illness
among humans. But this is the 1st time the virus
has infected pigs. Ebola's 3 other subtypes --
the Zaire, Sudan and Cote d'Ivoire strains -- can
cause deadly hemorrhagic fever in humans,
according to the World Health Organization [WHO].

"We're treating this as a matter of low public
health risk," said Caroline-Ann Coulombe, a WHO
officer in Manila. "But this is a new animal
species (to be infected), and in the Philippines
particularly swine are in contact with humans and
we do feel it needs more investigation." She said
the WHO was awaiting an official invitation to
send a team of experts to the Philippines.

The Wall Street Journal reported Friday [19 Dec
2008] that the Philippine government waited until
10 Dec 2008 to make the presence of the virus
public, although Manila authorities were notified
as early as 30 Oct 2008. The health and
agriculture secretaries took pains to assure the
public that pork is safe to eat if it is cooked
well -- even munching on roast pig during a 10 Dec 2008 news conference.

In the letter to FAO, Catbagan said the
Philippines has consistently acted in a
"transparent and responsible" manner in dealing
with the outbreak. That includes putting pork
exports on hold, and canceling a plan to send the
1st ever shipment to Singapore.

[Byline: Oliver Teves]

