[2]
Date: Wed 17 Dec 2006
From: Peter Roeder
<peter.roeder@taurusah.com>


When I was working at the Philippines Animal
Health Centre in the early 1990s, I remember
discussing the Ebola-Reston issue with Filipino
colleagues in the Bureau of Animal Industry who
were involved in trying to understand what had
happened. If I remember correctly, the primate
trade for medical research was a very complex and
not exactly transparent exercise. I recall that
premises which had housed monkeys from the
Philippines (offically only captive bred but
unofficially thought to be a mixture of captive
bred and wild caught) had also housed, even if
only temporarily in transit, monkeys from Africa.

Therefore, it seemed to me at the time that it
was possible that the Ebola-Reston virus could
conceivably have come from Africa, not
necessarily from the Philippines, and infected
Philippine monkeys there. One has to wonder if
the virus could have moved from there into
indigenous species capable of constituting a
reservoir (e.g., shrews, rodents, bats) and from
there infecting swine, both indigenous and
domesticated. It is an interesting scenario but,
of course, I could be completely wrong.

--
Peter Roeder BVetMed, MSc, PhD, MRCVS, OBE
Taurus Animal Health
Bordon
Hampshire GU35 8SY
UK

[I was working at WHO/HQ, Geneva in 1989 when the
Reston outbreak occurred. It was determined by
WHO that the Philippine monkeys were indeed held
for some hours in an airport transit warehouse
that also held a cage with 2 monkeys from Africa,
but those were tested and found to be negative. - Mod.JW]

